abstract: NIBLO'S GARDEN.--"La Favorita" was produced here last evening. Notwithstanding its frequent repetition, the attendance was satisfactory. We have little else to add. The performance was an equal one, and gave satisfaction. Signora STEFFANONE was in excellent voice, but sang very unvenly. Signor BENEVENTANO acted and sang with moderation, and was deserving of more applause than he received. SALVI maintained his position as a capital tenor and remarkably had actor--apparently to the entire satisfaction of himself.

abstract: A new work by TALVI is an event which cannot fail to attract considerable attention. abstract: If a war cloud, though no larger than a man's hand, be discernible on any part of the World's horizon, the barometer on 'Changethat most sensitive instrument- immediately gives token of the storm. abstract: YELLOW FEVER AT NATCHIZ.--We are glad to perceive that the pestilence was abating at Natchez at last accounts. From a total of 18 deaths, of which 17 were caused by yellow fever, on the 7th instant, the mortality by the 18th had fallen to 4, of which only 2 were from yellow fever. On the 19th there were no deaths ; and on the 20th 4, of which 3 were from yellow fever.

abstract: The Hunkers held a monster ratification meeting here to-night. It was one of the largest gatherings ever witnessed in this city. JAMES D. abstract: Better and better! Pleasant Autumn weather has reduced still lower the weekly list of deaths. abstract: Our bill of mortality, during the past week, shows a list of 198 deaths, of which 100 were children. Seven fatal cases of yellow fever are reported, and six malignant and five scarlet. The malignant cases may be set down as yellow fever, beyond all doubt. There were nineteen deaths by consumption, and sixteen by dysentery. Among the whole, sixteen died in the Almshouse, and only six were colored persons.

abstract: The Women's Convention reassembled this morning, when Rev. ANTOINETTE BROWN replied to Mr. BARKER's speech of yesterday. abstract: MURDER AND RAPE AT JAMAICA, L I.--On Sunday evening last, a young girl by the name of CATHARINE QUIGLEY was murdered near the village of Jamaica, Queens Co. abstract: ARREST OF LIQUOR-SELLERS.--On Saturday last warrants were served upon most of the hotel-keepers and liquor-sellers of the First Ward of Jersey City, charging them with selling liquor without a license. It is stated to be the intention of the opponents of the traffic to take the Wards in turn, and complain of the liquor-sellers in them.

abstract: FOUND DEAD.-A young man, 35 years of age, named David Sackett, formerly a clerk in Mr. Armstrong's clothing store, in Grand street, was found dead in Mr. Inglass stable, corner of Grand and Sixth-streets, between 1 and 2 o'clock yesterday afternoon. abstract: The car on which the late mail was burned was a common freight car, open only at the sides. When it was found to be on fire--it being in the night, and the train in rapid motion--there was no means of communicating the fact to the conductor or the engineer, except by the cry of "fire;" and the noise of the cars and machinery, in this case, rendered that mode ineffectual.
